      <lg xml:id="ITA17">
<l>maṟṟā riyalāvār vāṉavarkōṉ māmalarōṉ</l>
<l>cuṟṟum vaṇaṅkun toḻilāṉai – yoṟṟaip</l>
<l>piṟaiyirunta ceñcaṭaiyāṉ piṉceṉṟu mālaik</l>
<l>kuṟaiyirantu tāṉmuṭittāṉ koṇṭu</l>
      </lg>
      <lg xml:lang="en">
<l>Are there others to rival [him]? Going after the worker to whom all around<note xml:lang="en" place="foot">Here the adverbial cuṟṟum (“all around”) is slightly problematic, since it is difficult to see how two people (Indra and Brahmā) can bow all around the lord; perhaps we have to understand that they just crowd in on him in support for the request made by Śiva.</note></l>
<l>the king of the celestials [and] the one on the great flower bow,</l>
<l>the one with red matted hair in which the unique crescent moon sits took</l> 
<l>his<note xml:lang="en" place="foot">For metrical reasons the two absolutives irantu and koṇṭu appear separated while it makes perfect sense to read them as one complex verb form irantukoṇṭu, “begging on one’s own behalf”, which can be rendered in the translation by a possessive pronoun before kuṟai.</note> request to Māl, begged [and] succeeded.<note xml:lang="en" place="foot">This is a slightly veiled reference to Śiva asking Viṣṇu for help to get rid of Brahmā’s skull which was stuck to his hand (cf. Po. 46.1-3, Pū. 63.1f.).</note></l>
      </lg>
    </div>
